Special List:
CopyOnWriteArrayList (Best for high reads)
      This is the modern thread-safe alternative to a synchronized ArrayList.
            How it works: Every time you modify the list (add/remove), it creates a fresh copy of the entire underlying array.
            Thread Safety: Iterators use a snapshot of the array taken at the moment the iterator was created, so you won’t get a ConcurrentModificationException.
            Use Case: Best when you have many threads reading data, but very few threads writing (e.g., a cache of configuration settings).
      
            List<String> threadSafeList = new CopyOnWriteArrayList<>();
            threadSafeList.add("Data"); // Expensive operation (creates a copy)
Why “Copy-On-Write”?
  Because on every modification: Old Array → Copy → Modify → Replace
      list.add(10);
      list.add(20);
      Internally:
            Step 1: []
            Step 2: [10]         (new array created)
            Step 3: [10, 20]     (new array created again)
 Internal Working:
🔹 Structure: transient volatile Object[] array;
    Key points:
      Uses array internally
      volatile → ensures visibility across threads
      Uses ReentrantLock for writes
🔹 Write Operation (add)
      1. Acquire lock
      2. Copy old array
      3. Add new element
      4. Replace reference
      5. Release lock
🔹 Read Operation
      No lock needed ✅
      Reads directly from array
      That’s why reads are very fast
 Key Features
      Feature	            Value
      Thread-safe	            ✅
      Read performance	      Very fast
      Write performance	      Slow
      Iterator	            Fail-safe
 Fail-Safe Iterator:
      for(Integer i : list) {
          list.add(100); // NO exception
      }
       Why- Iterator works on snapshot (copy)
✅ Best Use Cases
      Read-heavy systems
      Rare writes
🔹 Examples
      Configuration data
      Event listeners
      Subscriber lists
❌ When NOT to Use
      Frequent updates ❌
      Large data ❌ Because copying is expensive
 Performance
      Operation	Time
      get()	      O(1)
      add()	      O(n)
      remove()	O(n)

🔹 1. Snapshot Iteration- CopyOnWrite:Iterator sees old copy
🔹 2. Locking Strategy
            Writes → lock
            Reads → no lock
🔹 3. Memory Tradeoff- More memory usage due to copying

Collections.synchronizedList (Old School)
      This wraps a standard ArrayList and synchronizes every method.
            How it works: It uses an internal lock. Only one thread can access any method at a time.
            Warning: You must manually synchronize when iterating over it, or it will crash.
            Use Case: When you have a high volume of writes and CopyOnWriteArrayList becomes too slow.
      
            List<String> syncList = Collections.synchronizedList(new ArrayList<>());
      🔹 Internal Working
            Uses single lock
            Every operation synchronized
      🔹 Drawback - Slow (global locking)

