To create a clean, annotation-free caching class, the most reliable approach is to wrap a ConcurrentHashMap. 
This ensures that your cache is thread-safe, meaning multiple parts of your application can read and write to it simultaneously without crashing or corrupting data.

import java.util.concurrent.ConcurrentHashMap;
import java.util.Map;
public class SimpleCache<K, V> {
    // Using ConcurrentHashMap for thread safety without synchronized blocks
    private final Map<K, V> storage = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();
    /**
     * Adds or updates a value in the cache.
     */
    public void put(K key, V value) {
        if (key != null && value != null) {
            storage.put(key, value);
        }
    }
    /**
     * Retrieves a value. Returns null if the key doesn't exist.
     */
    public V get(K key) {
        return storage.get(key);
    }
    /**
     * Removes a specific entry from the cache.
     */
    public void remove(K key) {
        storage.remove(key);
    }
    /**
     * Clears all cached data.
     */
    public void clear() {
        storage.clear();
    }
    /**
     * Returns the current size of the cache.
     */
    public int size() {
        return storage.size();
    }
}
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Create a cache for User objects indexed by their ID (String)
        SimpleCache<String, User> userCache = new SimpleCache<>();
        // Put data
        userCache.put("user_101", new User("Alice"));
        // Get data
        User cachedUser = userCache.get("user_101");
        System.out.println("Retrieved: " + cachedUser.getName());
        // Remove data
        userCache.remove("user_101");
    }
}
Thread Safety: By using ConcurrentHashMap, you avoid ConcurrentModificationException when one thread is reading while another is removing an item.
Generic Types: Using <K, V> allows you to reuse this same class for any data type (e.g., String keys with Integer values, or Long keys with CustomObject values).
No Magic: Unlike @Cacheable, there are no hidden proxies. If you call get(), it executes immediately, making it much easier to debug.

